snippet.textDisplay: Jenna cracks me up thinking it’s Bunny’s first bath.  Racers get a dip in a hydro tank and a body massage/rub down after every race. It cools them down, loosens tight muscles and allows trainers to find any sore muscles or injuries. They are only allowed to run 1-2 races a week so that’s two dips in the pool a week.  After adopting our first racer 18 yrs ago, we went to watch the races with our hound and toured the kennels to see what her life was like before.  We still board our hounds at the Birmingham Race Course Adoption Center when we are unable to take them with us on vacation.

snippet.textDisplay:
Jenna, you inspired me this year, a lot. Because of your patience with animals I took a leap and took in two kittens in need of an urgent home. It's been the craziest journey of my life so far. I also got a starving, abandoned cat who chose us as her safe yard to live in, to come inside this year and fully integrate with us! And now she's fat (actually a good thing) and part of our family! She reminds me of Bunny so much. Her name is Dwellie (because she dwelled in our yard for a long time) and she is now on her orthopedic bed, with her mouse toy, fast asleep. Dwellie was so scared, snappy, and not affectionate at all and now she leaps up to get that much closer to my hand for pets, will run towards me if she sees me, and is an extremely quiet and patient cat with a small treat addiction. She's spayed, missing a nipple and a front fang, and snagged a back claw somehow so it's permanently hyper-extended. But she doesn't seem to be in any pain as it's not torn, just healed wrong. We think a neighbour abandoned her upon moving out but before that, abused her.


The two other cats - one is JUST LIKE KERMIT, his name is Tux, and his twin sister, a tortie named Marmalade, is very Peach-like - were all that we were expecting to have. They're coming up on ten months old in mid-January. But Dwellie adopted us and we had no say in the matter beyond being so loving and patient. I'd go out on the deck without shoes in the July heat, just to give her some treats and earn her trust. I'd call for her, teach her her name, eventually giving her a blanket to lay down on and then a chair and finally a bed. Tux is absolutely in love with Dwellie, and Marmalade is a bit intimidated (she's small, Dwellie is huge) but they're learning to get along in their own way more and more.


Your patience and acceptance of animals "as they are" went a long way in my cats loving me back. My two kittens are indoors because I care, but I often take them out on a leash to explore the deck and plants. I accepted Marmalade for her need to be in my arms every night and kneading me, or sitting near me at all times, because she was and is so tiny. She loves treats, and a squishy strawberry I got for my autism. Tux is huge, muscled, and demands attention and food more than the average kitty - but he loves so, so hard and will "escort you" around the house to make sure nothing "attacks" you like a fly or a spider. Dwellie was accepted as she is and we met her there.


She likes to sit in front of my parent's bedroom space heater, so we have a routine of turning it on for her to warm up. She prefers to go outside to poop, but is slowly learning the litterbox. I think what won her over was one night a gang of raccoons tried to attack Dwellie and we made the split second decision to defend her against them as she was about to be killed. A switch flipped in her head, and she warmed to us so quickly it was comical. We took it slow but it only took a matter of a few months for her to have pictures in frames around our house because she was, and is, part of the family now. I'll never, ever let her go.


It's good that she's fat because she was starving and a starving, formerly fat cat can go into liver failure and drop dead quickly, so her body rebounded by packing on some extra chonk as a protection against liver problems - as the body wants to eat the liver, or something, so if she ever starves again (which she won't!) she'll be able to eat away at her fat stores instead. I have a vet friend and my dad is on good terms with an old-school vet. They both agree her weight is not a problem for now because she'll slowly lose it as her body comes to terms with her regular diet of locally caught salmon my mother's coworker preserves, some high-quality dry food, and extremely high quality canned food "that humans can eat if they wanted to." We're not at all rich - we're below the poverty line in Canada - but we take care of our animals like they are royalty because we know we'd want the same for ourselves.


2019 was so wild, thank you Jenna for inspiring me to do the best I could. I love your content. Never change.


- A fellow Virgo

They both agree her weight is not a problem for now because she'll slowly lose it as her body comes to terms with her regular diet of locally caught salmon my mother's coworker preserves, some high-quality dry food, and extremely high quality canned food "that humans can eat if they wanted to." We're not at all rich - we're below the poverty line in Canada - but we take care of our animals like they are royalty because we know we'd want the same for ourselves.


2019 was so wild, thank you Jenna for inspiring me to do the best I could. I love your content. Never change.


- A fellow Virgo
